{"cells":[{"source":"<a href=\"https://www.kaggle.com/mmmelggg/case-study-bicycle-sharing?scriptVersionId=88425842\" target=\"_blank\"><img align=\"left\" alt=\"Kaggle\" title=\"Open in Kaggle\" src=\"https://kaggle.com/static/images/open-in-kaggle.svg\"></a>","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown","outputs":[],"execution_count":0},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"fccd2e32","metadata":{"papermill":{"duration":0.015729,"end_time":"2022-02-21T23:38:10.286133","exception":false,"start_time":"2022-02-21T23:38:10.270404","status":"completed"},"tags":[]},"source":["**Statement of Business Task**\n","\n","This case study comes from work done for a data analytics certificate program. The task centered around answering the question about how a bike-sharing company's annual (also called \"members\") riders differ from their casual (those who purchase single-use or full-day passes) users. \n","\n","In the assigned hypothetical situation, this case study question was the first question of three to be answered for a marketing program for the bike-sharing company. With insights from the answers to these three questions, this company wanted to use their marketing program to achieve its goal of maximizing annual memberships. The hypothetical key stakeholders for this case study were the Director of Marketing, the company's marketing analytics team, and the company's executives. \n","\n","This case study required the following deliverables:     \n","    1. Statement of the business task\n","    2. Description of all data sources used\n","    3. Documentation of cleaning or manipulation of data\n","    4. Summary analysis\n","    5. Supporting visualizations and key findings"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"7a7ef6fd","metadata":{"papermill":{"duration":0.01475,"end_time":"2022-02-21T23:38:10.31577","exception":false,"start_time":"2022-02-21T23:38:10.30102","status":"completed"},"tags":[]},"source":["**Data Sources**\n","\n","For this case study, the program gave me access to historical trip data from a real company. The privacy policy allows for sharing of this data for non-commerical purposes.\n","\n","For this case study, I used data for a three month time period. The data covered the most recent quarter for which quarter data was available. This data came directly from the company and consists of all historical trip data for the time period. This data appeared to have been gathered by the company through an automated process as users took rides on the bicycles.\n","\n","Due to the companyâ€™s privacy policy, this data did not have information on where users live. In addition, the data could not be used to determine whether one user purchased mulitple single-use or full-day passes. \n","\n","The data consisted of 426,887 rows of individual rides with 13 columns in one csv file. The columns were named and contained the following information:\n","\n","ride_id = unique ride identifier<br>\n","rideable_type = type of bike<br>\n","started_at = time ride started, including the year, month, date, time<br>\n","ended_at = time ride started, including the year, month, date, time<br>\n","start_station_name = name of originating station<br>\n","start_station_id = station ID for originating station<br>\n","end_station_name = name of destination station<br>\n","end_station_id = station ID of destination station<br>\n","start_lat = latitude for originating location<br>\n","start_lng = longitude of originating location<br>\n","end_lat\tend_lng = latitude and longitude of destination location<br>\n","member_casual = whether user is casual or a member\n","\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"f1211c36","metadata":{"papermill":{"duration":0.015001,"end_time":"2022-02-21T23:38:10.345399","exception":false,"start_time":"2022-02-21T23:38:10.330398","status":"completed"},"tags":[]},"source":["**Documentation of Data Cleaning and Manipulation**\n","\n","I used a spreadsheet (LibreOffice) for data exploration and quality checks. The main reason for using this tool centers around needing practice with it. I used methods like sort, filter, and pivot tables, unless noted. After downloading and extracting the file which contained all the data, I stored it in a stable and secure location. \n","\n","I found and did the following to the file: <br><br>\n","The ride_id column contained all unique values.<br>\n","All fields contained the similar data in the same format.<br>\n","There were no typos or incorrect data entry.<br>\n","I trimmed leading and trailing spaces with the Trim function.<br>\n","Several fields had an apostrophe to force text, which I removed with Text to Column<br>\n","One row had missing values, so I deleted this row.<br>\n","Station_name fields and station_id fields correlated one to one.<br>\n","Latitute and Longitude combinations correlate to one station.<br>\n","I deleted the rideable_type column since it contained the same value for all records.<br>\n","I inserted a calculated column called weekday_end, which consisted of a number denoting day of the week.<br>\n","I verified each column had the correct format for the data.<br><br>"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"b47a5893","metadata":{"papermill":{"duration":0.015229,"end_time":"2022-02-21T23:38:10.375139","exception":false,"start_time":"2022-02-21T23:38:10.35991","status":"completed"},"tags":[]},"source":["**Analysis Summary**\n","\n","I summarized the following calculations in a sheet separate from the data:<br><br>\n","mean ride length (using AVERAGE()) = 22:06<br>\n","maximum ride length (using MAX()) = 15:30:24<br>\n","most popular day of the week (using mode()) = 3 (Tuesday)<br>\n","\n","Using pivot tables, I calculated the following:<br><br>\n","number of rides by casual users = 48,479<br>\n","number of rides by members = 378,407<br><br>\n","mean ride length by casual users = 1:35:47<br>\n","mean ride length by members = 12:41<br><br>\n","maxiumum ride length by casual users = 15:30:24<br>\n","maxiumum ride length by members = 3:13:31<br><br>\n","most popular day for casual users = Sunday<br>\n","most popular day for members = Tuesday<br><br>\n","\n","For mapping, I created pivot tables to calculate number of rides per each starting station, as a total by user type. I added a column to calculate the rank of the station in popularity for the user type because I thought it would facilitate mapping. I then created separate tables of the top 50 stations for each user type.\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"7f4e44bd","metadata":{"papermill":{"duration":0.014665,"end_time":"2022-02-21T23:38:10.405473","exception":false,"start_time":"2022-02-21T23:38:10.390808","status":"completed"},"tags":[]},"source":["**Key Findings**\n","\n","Casual users average ride is longer than members and a casual user has the longest ride. See visualization here https://drive.google.com/file/d/1PYiarPjYR5wE5z6dyV99qQRKpux9ir2V/view?usp=sharing<br><br>\n","\n","Casual users volums is highest on Sunday while members' highest volume day is Tuesday. See visualization here https://drive.google.com/file/d/1I6pNVGDv84YFepPNpGWDrP4j1T4jinMA/view?usp=sharing<br><br>\n","\n","High volume starting stations for casual users are different than members' high volume starting stations. One thing to note is that the company's headquarters shows up as the higest volume station for casual users, so if those users are employees, I might eliminate it in future analyses. See visualization here: https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/1/edit?mid=1D714Gr4n7N_yy4U9sBABtOwWpgUsEkQn&usp=sharing<br><br>\n","\n","\n"]}],"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"display_name":"R","language":"R","name":"ir"},"language_info":{"codemirror_mode":"r","file_extension":".r","mimetype":"text/x-r-source","name":"R","pygments_lexer":"r","version":"4.0.5"},"papermill":{"default_parameters":{},"duration":3.208212,"end_time":"2022-02-21T23:38:10.528006","environment_variables":{},"exception":null,"input_path":"__notebook__.ipynb","output_path":"__notebook__.ipynb","parameters":{},"start_time":"2022-02-21T23:38:07.319794","version":"2.3.3"}},"nbformat":4,"nbformat_minor":5}